sec.p:
All statistical analyses were performed using Review Manager (Version 5.4) and Stata software (Version 16.0). The analyses included the pooling of effect sizes, subgroup analyses, sensitivity analyses, and publication bias assessments. To minimise the influence of baseline differences, the effect size for each study was calculated using the mean change and its corresponding standard deviation. The first step involved calculating the difference in means:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:{M}_{change}={M}_{post}-{M}_{pre}$$\end{document}

where is the raw mean difference, is the reported mean post-intervention, and is the reported mean pre-intervention [17]. Then the SD of the change in means is calculated as follows [17]:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:{SD}_{change}=\sqrt{{SD}_{pre}^{2}+{SD}_{post}^{2}-(2\times\:r\times\:{SD}_{pre}\times\:{SD}_{post})}$$\end{document}
